  "opening_lines": [
    {
      "line": 1,
      "text": "Quarterly"
    },
    {
      "line": 4,
      "text": "pops esi"
    },
    {
      "line": 10,
      "text": "CH :"
    },
    {
      "line": 11,
      "text": "ELECTRONIC Robert Ishi"
    },
    {
      "line": 14,
      "text": "MICROCOMPUTER ART"
    },
    {
      "line": 17,
      "text": "A tiny chip of silicon helped me create these graphics. Admittedly, the chip is rather special - it’s a Synertek/MOS Technology"
    },
    {
      "line": 18,
      "text": "6502 microprocessor. This tiny computer-on-a-chip runs at 1,023,000 machine cycles per second and can do over 500,000 addition"
    },
    {
      "line": 19,
      "text": "or subtraction operations in one second. It’s the brain in my Apple II microcomputer."
    },
    {
      "line": 22,
      "text": "Of course, computer-generated art is not new. What is new, however, is the accessibility of computer power to the average artist."
    },
    {
      "line": 23,
      "text": "No longer is such power restricted to highly trained specialists time-sharing on multimillion dollar machines. The microcomputer"
    },
    {
      "line": 24,
      "text": "offers a powerful new tool for visual expression. I predict that we will see the rapid emergence of creative new imagery based on the"
    },
    {
      "line": 25,
      "text": "use of microcomputers - a positive fallout of the computer revolution."
    },
